<HEAD>$Adv11-13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Aug 11-13 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-AP Arts: Wizard of Oz</HEAD>
<HEAD>I Don't Think We're in Kansas Anymore, Toto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Arts Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anything's possible in Oz, and just about
everything's possible in Hollywood.
   Like Dorothy as a blonde.
   When shooting first began on ``The Wizard of Oz,'' director
Richard Thorpe put Judy Garland in a blond wig. He was later fired
and replaced by Victor Fleming (``Gone With the Wind'') and King
Vidor. Garland ditched the golden locks and played the movie in her
own hair and a fall.
   ``The Wizard of Oz,'' like most movies, abounds with anecdotes
and tales both tall and true.
   There's the story of the ragged coat Frank Morgan wore as
Professor Marvel. It was purportedly purchased from a second-hand
store in Los Angeles and, as the story goes, Morgan pulled out a
pocket one day and found the name L. Frank Baum sewn inside. Baum
wrote the orginal Oz stories.
   Or, when Dorothy first meets the Lion and slaps him for growling
at the Tin Man and Scarecrow, and the lion grabs his tail and
cries. Garland burst into giggles on the set and delayed the shoot.
Fleming, as the legend goes, took Garland behind one of the trees
and slapped her. The scene was shot and the take was good.
   Later, the director called the three vaudeville stars ``hams''
for dancing down the Yellow Brick Road without little Judy.
   And the vaudeville in Bert Lahr allowed him to come up with the
classic movie line, ``unusual weather we're having, ain't it?,''
when Dorothy and friends wake up in the poppy field during a
snowstorm.
   Ray Bolger, who played the Scarecrow, later said, ``We joked a
lot because that was the only way we could survive.''
   Every film has someone who's responsible for ``continuity.'' In
``Oz,'' that meant that every morning someone would count the straw
sticking out of Bolger's costume to make sure it was accurate in
terms of what had already been shot.
   Costumes and makeup took their toll on Bolger, Margaret Hamilton
(the Wicked Witch), Bert Lahr (the Lion) and Jack Haley (the Tin
Woodman). Bolger's skin began to wrinkle because of the Scarecrow
makeup and mask, Haley's 40-pound costume prevented him from
sitting between takes, Hamilton had a green tint to her skin even
when the movie was completed and her fake fingernails were always
popping off.
   Because the movie used more lights and electricity than any
other movie _ it was shot in Technicolor _ the set was unreasonably
hot. Sometimes, it would even smoke up. Lahr, whose costume was
extremely heavy and snug, was drenched in perspiration after
minutes.
   While stories about the ``The Wizard of Oz'' continue to
delight, the movie has grown from a childhood romp to the campy
comebacks of a jaded generation. Memo and note pads abound with
Dorothy's wide-eyed proclamation to Toto once they've landed in Oz:
``I don't think we're in Kansas anymore, Toto.''
   And the Wicked Witch of the West's admonition to Dorothy,
``Well, my little pretty, I can cause accidents, too,'' after
Dorothy says that dropping a house on the Wicked Witch of the East
was an accident, is now a popular one-liner.
   But most of all, ``The Wizard of Oz'' will always evoke happy
thoughts of home. As Dorothy said, ``If I ever go looking for my
heart's desire again, I won't look any further than my own back
yard because, if it isn't there, I never really lost it to begin
with.''
</TEXT>
