   HOLLYWOOD -- The movie industry thinks it has the perfect
antidote for its recessionary woes: actors who won't demand a
"percent of the gross" but are always animated.
   Literally.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Spurred by the success of "The Little Mermaid" and the
re-released "101 Dalmatians" from Walt Disney Co., nearly all
the major studios are rushing out full-length animated
features. In an age of spiraling costs, animated movies
rarely require the outlays of live-action films. There aren't
any big star egos to soothe or hefty star salaries to pay.
The demographics promise a large return when the films are
released on home video. And there's big potential in licensed
merchandise and theme park tie-ins.
   But the glut of entries won't make marketing the films
easy. The battle will be joined Nov. 22 with the head-to-head
release of Disney's "Beauty and the Beast" and a Universal
Pictures sequel, "An American Tail: Fievel Goes West."
   Other animated films headed for the starting gate include
"FernGully . . . The Last Rainforest" from News Corp.'s
Twentieth Century Fox. Samuel Goldwyn Co. will release
"Rock-a-Doodle," a movie by Don Bluth, creator of "The Land
Before Time." Turner Entertainment, the Turner Broadcasting
System unit that just bought Hanna-Barbera Productions Inc.,
is working on "Tom &amp; Jerry: The Movie." And next summer
Paramount Pictures, a unit of Paramount Communications Inc.,
will release an animated film aimed at urban youngsters
called "Bebe's Kids."
   Until recently, Disney had the animated field to itself,
re-releasing its classics every few years and throwing in an
occasional new film. But as Disney geared up so that it could
release one new animated film a year, the competition woke
up.
   Now, the studios are vying with each other to find release
dates when the competition will be minimal. That isn't easy,
though. Many film executives believe animated features play
well only in a few narrow periods when families can go to the
movies together. Fox originally planned to release
"FernGully," its first animated feature since 1983, this
month. But it didn't want to slug it out with the other two
pre-Thanksgiving openings so it moved its picture to next
Easter.
   Another major problem facing all of the studios except
Disney is that their films usually don't have characters
children recognize. Nor do they have the Disney "seal of
approval" that tells parents a film is probably good, clean
and safe even for young children.
   To make up for that, the studios are working overtime to
reach potential audiences with advance details about their
new stories and characters. Marketing and publicity
executives at Fox have begun their campaign to raise
awareness for "FernGully" six months before its release. They
recently sent out elaborate press kits, added a trailer for
the film to the studio's "Home Alone" video and started
exploring direct-mail options.
   Goldwyn's "Rock-a-Doodle" won't open until next April, but
the company arranged for a "Rock-a-Doodle" float in this
year's Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade, including a two-minute
production number in front of the store. Beginning next year,
Scholastic will insert "Rock-a-Doodle" posters and study
guides into teachers' magazines, reaching six million kids.
Goldwyn is also linking up with International Dairy Queen
Inc. and Quaker Oats Co.'s Life cereal.
   Disney and Universal have also been priming the publicity
pump for months, even though "Beauty" is based on a famous
fairy tale and "Fievel Goes West" is a sequel featuring a
fairly well-known character. Disney has formed promotional
ties with Burger King Corp. and Colgate Palmolive Co.;
Universal, a unit of Japan's Matsushita Electric Industrial
Co., is linked to PepsiCo Inc.'s Pizza Hut and RJR Nabisco's
Nabisco Biscuit Co.
   This will be the third time that the two studios have
opened animated features on the same day, a strategy that
runs contrary to the usual Hollywood approach. In 1988,
Disney's "Oliver &amp; Co." took in $53.1 million, beating
Universal's "The Land Before Time" at $48.1 million. In 1986,
the original "An American Tail" won with $47.5 million;
Disney's re-release of "Song of the South" took in $17.7
million.
   Many industry watchers expect Universal's mouse to beat
Disney's beast in their opening weekend. That's because
Universal's movie will be released on about 1,400 screens.
Disney is holding its film to 900 screens, adding 400 to 600
more on Christmas Day.
   Steven Spielberg's Amblin Entertainment is developing the
Fievel films into a powerful franchise. The immigrant mouse
is at the center of a merchandising and licensing program,
and the studio is promoting the movie at its theme parks.
   Disney is pitching "Beauty" as an "event." It took the
unusual step of previewing a "work-in-progress" copy of the
film in late September at the prestigious New York Film
Festival, making it the first ever animated movie to be shown
at the event.
   Disney recently showed the same version to an audience of
Motion Picture Academy of America members in Hollywood.
Programs distributed at the screening featured a letter from
Disney Vice Chairman Roy Disney and Jeffrey Katzenberg,
chairman of Walt Disney Studios, telling Academy members of
the success of the New York screening.
   "Animation is indeed a unique and collaborative process. .
. . Yet no animated film has ever received an Academy Award
for Best Picture," the letter said. "We hope you'll leave
tonight's screening with a new or renewed appreciation for
this very special art form."
</TEXT>
