<HEAD>MGM-Pathe Deal Closes, Finally</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By E. SCOTT RECKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pathe Communications Corp.'s $1.36
billion buyout of MGM-UA is finally a done deal, but whether the
historic studio and its trademark lion will roar again remains
uncertain.
   The new enterprise, like the pending purchase of MCA Inc. by
Matsushita Electric Industrial Co., seeks to exploit an
international hunger for Hollywood entertainment. Pathe's holdings
are mainly European.
   But unlike robust Sony Corp., which last year bought Columbia
Pictures Entertainment, Giancarlo Parretti's cash-poor Pathe
labored for months to close the MGM-UA deal.
   Bringing success to the new studio will be a struggle, analysts
say.
   Wall Street experts have said it will take at least $500 million
and several years to revive MGM-UA, whose recent releases range
from hits such as ``Rain Man,'' to box office bombs such as
``Desperate Hours.''
   Pathe has mortgaged its future, said Jessica Reif, an analyst
for First Boston Corp. The new studio's budget and its profits,
Reif said, will be tied up in the sale of foreign, domestic and
home video rights to nearly every movie in the combined
Pathe-MGM-UA libraries for the next 10 years.
   Speaking on condition of anonymity, an executive for a rival
studio said the newly formed MGM-Pathe Communications Co. will need
hit movies fast. He estimated the price paid may have been double
the studio's worth.
   Pathe officials say they paid a fair price and intend to
recapture the once-legendary status of MGM.
   Parretti spokeswoman Arlene Cattani said the Italian financier
took possession of the studio and its Leo the Lion trademark at
11:07 a.m. PST.
   A beaming Parretti later was greeted in his offices with a
surprise from his staff - a real lion named Sudan - to personify
the deal's closing. He gingerly sidled up to the 450-pound brute
for a few quick photographs.
   ``Our goal is to make the MGM lion roar again,'' Parretti said
in a statement. ``We will continue to develop the kind of product
that has made the MGM and UA names legendary for generations, while
building on Pathe's global presence.''
   The buyout pays stockholders of MGM-UA a total of $21.50 per
share. Earlier payments of $4 a share were made this summer.
   Craig Parsons, a spokesman for Pathe, said Parretti would become
chief executive officer. He and his longtime associate, Florio
Fiorini, will be named co-chairmen.
   Pathe Entertainment's Alan Ladd Jr., part of a host of film
executives who headed MGM-UA, will run the new studio, Parsons
said.
   Beverly Hills-based Pathe produces television and feature films.
It also has a variety of European movie-related holdings.
   As part of the complicated transaction, MGM-UA will buy Pathe's
assets for $700 million, raised in part through the sale of rights
to a variety of Pathe, MGM and United Artists film and television
properties. That $700 million will then be used to help buy MGM-UA.
   Independently, Pathe raised $600 million through stock sales to
unidentified European investors.
   Those entities are believed to include Parretti's principal
holding company, Com Finance S.A. of Luxembourg; his Melia
International, one of the world's largest travel agencies; and the
Spanish real estate business Renta Inmobiliaria S.A.
   An earlier MGM-UA sale to Pathe fell apart last spring when Time
Warner Inc. backed out of its agreement to finance $650 million of
the deal.
   Pathe spokesman Parsons said company officials are ``very
comfortable'' with production financing, which will be partially
underwritten by ``one new film a month,'' he said.
   No new debt is involved in the deal, Parsons said. MGM-UA
currently has about $400 million in debt and Pathe owes $300
million.
   For MGM-UA's current management, the future is unclear. Chief
executive Jeffrey Barbakow and studio chief Richard Berger did not
return phone calls seeking comment Thursday.
   MGM-UA majority stockholder Kirk Kerkorian offered the Culver
City-based studio for sale in April 1988.
   A spectrum of suitors - including Japan's Sony and C. Itoh,
Rupert Murdoch's News Corp., the Walt Disney Co. and the Dutch
conglomerate PolyGram - expressed interest in a deal, lured largely
by the United Artists library, which included the ``Rocky'' and
James Bond movies.
</TEXT>
