<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 9-10, bgn, `Lee's neighborhood' to CORRECT to Pino
sted Vito; SUBS 12th graf, `As Sal,' to CORRECT to Torturro as Pino sted
Edson as Vito; Movie opens June 30</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>At the Movies: ``Do the Right Thing'' ^By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Arts Editor</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   When Island Pictures released ``She's Gotta Have It,'' about a
sexually independent young woman, Spike Lee was lionized as the
leader of a new wave of independent filmmaking. He had made the 1986
lusty black-and-white movie for an amazing $175,000.
   He spent millions more for ``Do the Right Thing,'' and with this
frank, realistic and brutal portrait of racism and its byproducts,
the brash young filmmaker has entered the mainstream.
   Race was not an issue in ``She's Gotta Have It.'' In his last
film, ``School Daze,'' Columbia Pictures' biggest grosser for 1988,
Lee was strident and polemical in his treatment of racial issues.
But in ``Do the Right Thing,'' he allows the movie itself to unravel
and define bigotry.
   The theme for the movie's title comes from a speech made by the
late black activist Malcolm X in December 1964: ``Racism is a human
problem and a crime that is absolutely so ghastly that a person who
is fighting racism is well within his rights to fight against it by
any means necessary until it is eliminated.''
   Malcolm X, and the late Nobelist Martin Luther King Jr., both
play an indirect role in the movie, which takes place in a
lower-middle-class neighborhood in the Bedford-Stuyvesant section of
Brooklyn. It is a longing to include photographs of the late civil
rights leaders on a ``wall of fame'' in a pizza parlor run by an
Italian that sparks a tragic racial confrontation. The Italian owner
has only the pictures of white Italian-Americans on his wall, such
as Frank Sinatra and Sophia Loren.
   It is a sweltering summer in Bedford-Stuyvesant. Perspiration
runs freely, as do fire hydrants and tempers.
   Sal (Danny Aiello) and his two sons, Vito and Pino, open their
pizzeria to start a new day. Da Mayor (Ossie Davis), an ancient
resident who spends his time washing down the yesteryears with a
bottle of beer, sweeps up; Mookie (Lee) arrives in Dodgers shirt
(they were once the Brooklyn Dodgers, folks) ready to do his
delivery chores.
   On the street, Radio Raheem, a young man of few words and an
intense scowl, lumbers about with a ghetto blaster the size of a
minitruck forcing the world to listen to rap music. The stuttering
Smiley lopes about trying to sell pictures of King and Malcolm X.
Buggin Out, the local activist, grouses about how there are no
blacks on the ``wall of fame,'' and yet only blacks and Hispanics
frequent the pizza parlor.
   Lee's neighborhood mosaic slowly takes shape with sharp images of
human character. Tensions and conflicts abound: Mookie and the young
woman who gave birth to his son; Radio Raheem and the Hispanic kids;
Radio Raheem and Sal; Buggin Out and Sal; Sal and Pino; Vito and
Pino; Mookie and Pino.
   It is the final confrontation between the hothead and racist Pino
and Radio Raheem that culminates in the movie's violent end. Raheem
is murdered by police; people on the block respond by destroying
Sal's pizzeria.
   Lee does not set up a frenzied, random or mob-inspired reaction.
Indeed, it is Mookie, a character who easily talks to everyone and
who plays the role of peacekeeper, who casts the first stone. He is,
as Malcolm X advised, doing whatever is necessary to fight racism.
   As Sal, the Italian who has run a business in a black
neighborhood for 25 years, Aiello is splendid. Davis is endearing as
the downtrodden Da Mayor, and his wife, Ruby Dee, has a wonderful
character in Da Mayor's love interest, Mother Sister. John Torturro
does a believable stupid punk as the racist Pino, and Bill Nunn is
menacing as Raheem.
   The movie introduces Rosie Perez in the role of Tina, Mookie's
girlfriend. She also does some explosive dancing with the opening
titles. However, as an actress, her lines are muddled.
   Lee has created something of a repertory company with his films,
and one sees familiar faces in them all. His sister, Joie Lee, who
co-starred in ``She's Gotta Have It,'' returns as Mookie's gracious
sister, Jade, who is adored by Sal. Giancarlo Esposito, who has
co-starred in Lee's two major releases, plays Buggin Out.
   Esposito has found his niche with Lee: In ``She's Gotta Have
It,'' he was a nacissistic dandy; in ``School Daze,'' he was a
narcissistic fraternity brother; as Buggin Out, he's self-righteous.
   As for Lee, he has never really thought of himself as an actor.
Yet, he always puts in a star performance. His direction is tight,
and the mood he creates leaves one as hot as the characters on the
screen.
   Lee has a powerful movie, whose truths may repel those who
continue to deny that racism is indeed woven into the fabric of
American life.
   The 40 Acres and a Mule Filmworks production is rated R.
</TEXT>
