<HEAD>With BC-AP Arts: Disney's World</HEAD>
<HEAD>DUELING FANTASY WORLDS: Mickey vs. King Kong</HEAD>
<HEAD>Hollywood Comes to Florida in Challenge to Disney Film Park</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhotos</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From King Kong's banana breath to E.T. From
Jaws to the 1906 San Francisco earthquake.
   Universal Studios is arriving in Orlando like gangbusters to
compete with the oldest established entertainment show in town.
   The $600 million Universal Studios Florida, based on some of
Hollywood's great movies, goes public in May, exactly a year after
the Disney-MGM Studios theme park opened for business a few miles
down the road.
   ``Come to Universal and ride the movies,'' says Steven
Spielberg, the bearded movie genius acting as creative consultant
for the 440-acre attraction.
   Company executives speak in terms of waging war against Walt
Disney World for the hearts, minds and pocketbooks of the millions
of tourists who will be dividing their attention between the
competing studio theme parks.
   ``I think they're very vulnerable,'' says Jay Stein, an MCA vice
president, about the Disney-MGM Studios.
   ``It IS a little like war. It means that when you invade you
make damn sure that your army is big enough and strong enough to
win.''
   The Florida attraction is a bigger, modernized version of
Universal's studio tour in California and is owned jointly by MCA
Inc. and the Rank Organization of London. Stein is president of the
division that created and built the park, MCA Recreation Services.
   Company officials say the key differences between their park and
Disney's is Universal's more sophisticated technology and its
``full-fledged involvement of the customer'' in each of the 15
attractions. They speak of ``super-realistic technology'' providing
``wrap-around experiences'' for young and old.
   In a blunt attack on the competition, Stein said in a recent
interview that ``what the Disney-MGM Studios are offering their
guests is approximately one-third of what we're offering. ...
Across the board, we're going to deliver a more impressive
entertainment experience.''
   Stein acknowledged, however, that the Disney organization was
``a strong, well-financed company with a marketing potential that
is intimidating at worst.''
   Because of that, he said, Universal ``needs to create and
deliver an entertainment experience that is so different and
superior that we can assure ourselves that we're going to capture
enough segments of the market to make this thing profitable.''
   Stein and MCA President Sid Sheinberg have for years disputed
Disney Chairman Michael Eisner's claims that the Disney-MGM Studios
theme park is the realization of Walt Disney's ideas from 50 years
ago.
   Stein and Sheinberg contend that Disney copied the concept from
Universal's Studio Tour, which has been in operation in the
Hollywood area since 1964, and that Eisner rushed into construction
to beat Universal into Florida.
   Eisner and other Disney officials usually soft-pedal the
criticism and the rivalry, insisting that the competition is good
for each other as well as Florida.
   Besides the theme park attractions, Universal Studios Florida
has the largest movie and television production area outside
Hollywood. It has three times the amount of sound-stage space that
Disney has.
   Production has been under way since 1988.
   Scheduled to go before the cameras this year, studio executives
say, are 13 feature films and 500 television episodes.
   The back lot tour includes 50 locations, including famed
Hollywood Boulevard, a New England Village, the San Francisco Wharf
and New York's Penn Station. There are 40 restaurants and snack
shops, including Schwab's Drug Store, the Studio Commissary and
Mel's Diner from ``American Graffiti.''
   Also a part of the complex will be the first Hard Rock Cafe in
Florida.
   With Universal's long tradition of blending public participation
and filmmaking, the Florida park encourages superlatives:
   _ ``Kongfrontation'' pits a skyway tram containing 50 people
against the 37-foot tall, computer-animated gorilla in what is
billed as the largest sound stage in the world. King Kong will be
so real that visitors will be able to smell his banana breath. The
six-story King Kong building has 50 facades modeled after midtown
Manhattan.
   _ In ``Jaws,'' a 24-foot-long, computerized shark weighing three
tons crunches its jaws onto a 40-passenger boat on 7-acre Amity
Bay, rocking the craft in both directions before the shark is
``killed.''
   _ A subway train carrying 200 guests into a San Francisco
station is buffetted by an ``earthquake,'' a re-creation of the
1906 San Francisco temblor that measured 8.3 on the Richter scale.
Trains crash into each other, the overhead roadway comes tumbling
down and 60,000 gallons of water flood the scene.
   _ ``Ghostbusters'' is a re-creation of the largest set ever
built on a Hollywood sound stage: eight-stories high. The action is
a special effects thriller, with 13 larger-than-life mechanical
ghosts getting zapped by Neutrana Wand beams until their
ectoplasmic energy explodes.
   _ Spielberg's pet project, ``E.T. The Extra-Terrestrial,'' is a
soaring, obstacle-filled adventure on a dirt bike. It starts with a
chase through a forest and takes the visitor all the way to E.T.'s
home, the Green Planet.
   The movie-themed rides and participatory attractions include a
high-speed chase inside the world of Hanna-Barbera cartoons, a
``Phantom of the Opera'' horror make-up show and visitor input into
Alfred Hitchcock's stylized thrillers.
   And so it goes, one ``funtastic'' happening after another in the
park that officials say will take visitors two days to cover fully.
   Universal plans a ``soft opening'' in early May. The official
grand opening is June 7, with Spielberg and a collection of
Hollywood stars presiding.
   Spielberg, who dreamed up ``E.T.,'' ``Jaws'' and other film
fantasies, calls his job as creative consultant a storyteller's
dream come true.
   ``We've made the movie experience something that fans can see,
feel, touch and smell,'' he says.
   The park's most ambitious undertaking, ``Back to the Future,''
will not be ready for the park's opening.
   It will have two adjacent theaters, each measuring 80 feet in
diameter, and use projected images along with complex motion
simulators topped with Delorean automobiles. Visitors will ride 12
of the cars in each dome as they go crashing through the centuries
with the mad scientist Doc Brown.
   Because of the complex technology, it is taking longer to build
than originally contemplated, said its inventor, Peter Alexander,
vice president of shows and rides for MCA's Recreational Services
Group.
   ``It's probably the most responsive and complex motion simulator
ever built,'' said Alexander.
   Nickelodeon, the TV network for kids, celebrated its 10th
birthday in March by beginning construction of a new home at the
Orlando park.
   The Nickelodeon production complex will consist of two sound
stages and an interactive entertainment area for children. It will
produce shows here throughout the year, and visitors to the park
will be able to audition for shows as well as to view production,
video, audio and control room operations.
   Universal expects to draw at least 5 million people in its first
year, and Stein and other officials say those who see will become
``instant converts'' passing the word on to others.
   ``We're going to be the new kid on the block, and people are
going to give us a try,'' he said. ``And we're going to deliver.''
</TEXT>
