<HEAD>MGM Grand to Build Movie Theme Park in Las Vegas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By E. SCOTT RECKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MGM Grand Inc. said Tuesday it will
spend $700 million to convert a Las Vegas golf course into a movie
theme park and a 5,000-room hotel-casino, gambling on luring
families to ``the best mouse trap in town.''
   ``I remember the days when Las Vegas lived almost entirely on
the high roller,'' MGM Grand chairman Fred Benninger said at a news
conference at the Beverly Hills Hotel. ``You can't do that
anymore.''
   The site is on the Las Vegas Strip location where the Tropicana
Country Club and Marina Hotel and Casino now stand. Benninger
wouldn't reveal how much MGM Grand paid for those properties.
   Other details were sketchy as well, although conceptual drawings
showed towering spires and domes, like a futuristic version of
Sleeping Beauty's Castle at Disneyland.
   MGM Grand, owned by Beverly Hills billionaire Kirk Kerkorian,
said last month it might build the theme park on a 60-acre site
beside the Desert Inn, which it owns and is promoting as a top-end
hotel-casino.
   The new theme park site, at 115 acres, is nearly twice as large.
Benninger said finding enough space was a more important
consideration than money.
   The new MGM Grand Hotel and theme park are tentatively expected
to open by late 1992.
   Benninger said he was confident the complex, with hotel rooms
costing about $40 a night, would cash in on the trend toward family
tourism in Las Vegas that began with the opening of Circus Circus a
decade ago.
   Las Vegas will count more than 18 million visitors this year, up
from 11 million in 1980. Its population has boomed from 300,000
eight years ago to more than 700,000.
   Las Vegas officials have said for years that the city needed a
major theme park to help attract families. A water theme park,
built on the Las Vegas Strip five years ago, has been extremely
successful.
   ``Clearly the theme park idea is one that has been looked at for
quite a while,'' said Harold Vogel, veteran entertainment analyst
for Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. ``It's an adult resort, and now they're
going to extend it so the rest of the family members can enjoy it
too.''
   Benninger said movie themes had proved an enduring lure to
tourists, as proved by expansions of Walt Disney Co. and MCA Inc.'s
Universal Studios into Florida movie theme parks.
   ``There has always been competition in Las Vegas,'' Benninger
said. ``I'm not worried about competition. We're building the best
mouse trap in town.''
   Benninger said MGM Grand will add 4,300 rooms to the 700-room
Marina at a cost of about $250 million. The theme park, which will
cost about $450 million, will include a working film and television
studio, although he said it might have just one sound stage.
   It is anticipated that the complex will employ 7,000 workers.
   Other details were sketchy. A name for the complex, and even its
designers, have yet to be selected. Benninger wouldn't reveal
details about the attractions being considered, although he said
there were many.
   He said ``two or three organizations'' had approached him about
possible partnerships and left open the possibility of finding
another partner.
   Benninger said MGM Grand regarded the development as a prototype
and had already received calls from unidentified organizations
about developing similar complexes elsewhere.
   MGM Grand, a separate company from MGM-UA Communications Corp.,
owns an all-frills Los Angeles-New York airline as well as the
Desert Inn. It also retains rights to a stylized version of the
famous MGM lion.
   Kerkorian, 72, had sold and bought back bits and pieces of
MGM-UA Communications for two decades, a period during which he
also traded Las Vegas hotels the way most people buy cars.
   Then last month, Australia's Qintex Group agreed to purchase
MGM-UA _ including the original lion logo _ for $1.5 billion,
outbidding media mogul Rupert Murdoch by $100 million.
   A fire at the original MGM Grand Hotel, which Kerkorian built in
1973, killed 84 people in 1980. In 1985, Kerkorian sold the hotel
and its sister hotel in Reno to Bally Manufacturing Co. of Chicago
for nearly $500 million.
