<HL> Movie Makers Hope Long Summer
Is Hot With Sequels and Comedies
---
By Laura Landro
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 05/14/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> KO GW WCI MGM NWS DIS TRSP DEG OPC MCA
MOVIES, RECORDS, RECORDING STUDIOS (FLX) </IN>
<TEXT>
   Amid general optimism about the summer season, the movie industry is buzzing with two big questions: Will Paramount Pictures rake in even more at the box office with "Beverly Hills Cop II" than with the original? 
And will Columbia Pictures be raked over the coals with the costly "Ishtar"? 

   Summer, which typically provides 40% of the industry's annual take at the box office, is long this year, with Memorial Day a week earlier than usual and Labor Day a week later. 
And just one or two blockbusters during the season could help to push 1987's receipts ahead of 1984's record $4.03 billion, according to A.D. Murphy, who tracks box-office results for the industry publication Variety. 

   "To set a new annual record," Mr. Murphy says, "we only need to be $250 million ahead of last year," when box-office receipts totaled $3.8 billion. 
He notes that the first 17 weeks of this year were $150 million ahead of the same period last year. 

   "The box office has been good for four or five months," adds Terry Semel, president of Warner Communications Inc.'s Warner Bros. unit. 
"On paper, at least, it looks like it's going to be a big summer." 

   Theater owners are optimistic, too. 
Ronald Leslie, who heads AMC Entertainment Inc., one of the nation's largest theater chains, expects at least 10 films to be big hits and three or four to be blockbusters. 
"This may be the best summer in 20 years," he says. 
"We sure need it." 

   Some studios really need it, too. 
Many of the season's movies will have to draw large audiences to cover costs, let alone make a profit. 
"There are a lot of very big expensive films this year," says Philip Garfinkle, senior vice president of Entertainment Data Inc. Mr. Garfinkle, whose company analyzes box-office data, adds that in each of the past three summers only nine pictures -- out of some 40 to 50 a season -- had revenues of over $40 million, thus qualifying as hits. (About 60 movies are scheduled for release this summer.) 

   The riskiest big-budget picture, most industry executives agree, is "Ishtar," which stars Warren Beatty and Dustin Hoffman as failed musicians who get caught up in shenanigans and intrigue in Morocco. 
The film, opening tomorrow, was initially scheduled for release last Christmas but was late and over budget. 
Although Columbia, a unit of Coca-Cola Co., hasn't confirmed the figures, industry executives estimate that the movie cost more than $40 million to produce and expect an additional $10 million will be spent on distribution and marketing. 

   The movie has attracted a lot of press, mostly for its huge budget (an average movie nowadays costs about $15 million). 
It may do well, gauging by the moderately favorable reviews it has already received in the major newsweeklies, where critics have tended to be deferential toward its big stars. 
Newsweek, for example, rated it "the kind of movie you smile at a lot and leave thinking, hey, that was a pleasant $5 worth of fun." 

   But a lot of $5 bills will have to change hands to make "Ishtar" a success. 
Industry executives say it will have to bring in more than $150 million just to break even. 

   The producers of "Beverly Hills Cop II," Don Simpson and Jerry Bruckheimer, also spent plenty on their movie-about $30 million. 
But industry executives say it is virtually sure to be a blockbuster. 
The first "Beverly Hills Cop," which introduced Eddie Murphy as a wiseacre Detroit street cop transplanted to Beverly Hills, cost $15 million and grossed more than $237 million in the U.S. alone. 
If Paramount, a unit of Gulf &amp; Western Inc., has another hit in a movie version of the classic television series "The Untouchables" -- as many exhibitors expect -- the company could walk away with the lion's share of the box office this summer. 

   There are other sequels to chose from as well, including Warner Bros.' 
"Superman IV"; MGM/UA Communications Co.'s "The Living Daylights," a James Bond movie featuring Timothy Dalton as the latest 007; and "Revenge of the Nerds II" from News Corp.'s Twentieth Century Fox Film Corp. 
For fans of the canine star of "Benji," Walt Disney Co. is bringing him back in "Benji the Hunted." 

   MCA Inc.'s Universal Pictures had planned to release "Jaws III" in early July. 
But Tom Pollock, the studio's head, acknowledges that the mechanical shark has been giving the studio some problems. 
He now expects to release the film before the summer's end. 

   In the meantime, Universal has high hopes for two other films. 
Like Paramount, Universal plans to release a movie based on an old television series -- a comedy treatment of "Dragnet" starring Dan Aykroyd. 
The other offering, "Harry and the Hendersons," is a fantasy adventure about a mythical beast adopted by a vacationing family. 
Produced under the aegis of Steven Spielberg's Amblin Entertainment, "Harry" opens June 5. 

   The picture Mr. Spielberg is most closely associated with this summer, Warner Bros.' 
"Innerspace," updates a concept that worked years ago in "Fantastic Voyage": A test pilot is miniaturized and injected into another person's body. 
Warner is also counting on appealing to a wide range of audiences with "Full Metal Jacket," a Vietnam drama directed by veteran Stanley Kubrick; "The Lost Boys," a teen-oriented flick about adolescent vampires; and an adaptation of the John Updike novel "The Witches of Eastwick," starring Cher, Susan Sarandon and Michelle Pfieffer as modern-day witches, and Jack Nicholson as the devil. 

   In addition to such big-budget pictures as "Beverly Hills Cop II," exhibitors are betting on a number of more modest films. 
Among the comedies are Tri-Star Pictures Inc.'s "Nadine," starring Jeff Bridges and Kim Basinger; Disney's "Adventures in Babysitting" and "Ernest Goes to Camp"; and MGM/UA's "Spaceballs," a science-fiction spoof produced by the comedian Mel Brooks. 
Paramount's "Back to the Beach" marks the return of Annette Funicello and Frankie Avalon. 

   Exhibitors are also hopeful about two action-adventure movies starring Arnold Schwarzenegger: Tri-Star's "The Running Man" and Fox's "Predator." 

   Besides "Ishtar," Columbia is releasing "Roxanne," with Steve Martin as a contemporary Cyrano De Bergerac, and "La Bamba," about the life of singer Richie Valens. 
In an unusual move, the studio plans to release the latter in both English and Spanish to draw Hispanic audiences. 

   Among the few wide-release children's movies this summer is Samuel Goldwyn Co.'s "The Chipmunk Adventure," which stars the animated cartoon creatures in their film debut and opens May 22. 
On July 7, Disney will re-release the animated classic "Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs." 

   Perhaps the most unusual promotion of the season is that for De Laurentiis Entertainment Group Inc.'s "The Million Dollar Mystery." 
Moviegoers get to solve the mystery of where $1 million is hidden in the movie -- and one lucky viewer will actually win the money. 

