<HEAD>Stoppard's Debut Film Awarded Golden Lion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VENICE, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   English playwright Tom Stoppard's debut
movie ``Rosencrantz and Guildenstern Are Dead'' received the top
prize Saturday at the 47th Venice Film Festival amid boos and
whistles from some of the media.
   The film, starring actor Richard Dreyfuss, reinterprets
Shakespeare's ``Hamlet'' from the point of view of the prince's two
old school chums, Rosencrantz and Guildenstern, who become
unwittingly involved in the power play between Hamlet and his
stepfather.
   Stoppard's 1966 play by the same name was a hit, but the film
was not predicted to take the Golden Lion prize despite favorable
reviews.
   The favorite, Martin Scorsese's ``Goodfellas,'' won the
second-place Silver Lion Award for direction. The film depicts life
in the American underworld, with Oscar-winning actor Robert De Niro
in a supporting role.
   The award for Best Actress went to Gloria Munchmeyer for her
starring role in Chilean director Silvio Caiozzi's film ``The Moon
in the Mirror.''
   The Best Actor award went to Oleg Borisov, protagonist of ``The
Only Witness'' by Bulgarian director Michail Pandurski.
   New Zealand director Jane Campion's ``An Angel at My Table'' won
the jury's ``special grand prize'' and received a long standing
ovation.
   A nine-person jury, headed by American author Gore Vidal, judged
21 films from 18 countries.
</TEXT>
