<HEAD>Stoppard's Debut Film Unexpectedly Awarded Golden Lion</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with Stoppard film winning top prize.
No pickup</NOTE>
<HEAD>By DENNIS REDMONT</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VENICE, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   English playwright Tom Stoppard's debut
movie, ``Rosencrantz and Guildenstern Are Dead,'' captured the top
prize today at the Venice Film Festival.
   The film, starring Richard Dreyfuss, reinterprets Shakespeare's
``Hamlet'' from the point of view of the prince's two old school
chums, Rosencrantz and Guildenstern, who become unwittingly
involved in, and ultimately victims of, the power play between
Hamlet and his stepfather.
   A screen treatment of Stoppard's 1966 hit tragi-comic play by
the same name, the film was not generally expected to take the
Golden Lion prize despite the favorable reviews it received after
its screening.
   The favorite had been Martin Scorcese's ``Goodfellas,'' which
instead won the second place Silver Lion Award for direction. The
film provides a vividly realistic portrait of life in the American
underworld, with Oscar-winning actor Robert De Niro in a supporting
role.
   The award for Best Actress went to Gloria Munchmeyer for her
starring role in Chilean director Silvio Caiozzi's film ``La Luna
En El Espejo'' (The Moon in the Mirror).
   The Best Actor award went to Oleg Borisov, protagonist of
``Edinstvenijat Svidetel,'' (The Only Witness) by Bulgarian
director Michail Pandurski.
   New Zealand director Jane Campion's entry, ``An Angel at My
Table,'' won the jury's ``special grand prize,'' and received a
long standing ovation from an appreciative crowd at the awards
ceremony.
   A nine-person jury headed by American author Gore Vidal judged
the 21 films from 18 countries running in the competition at this
year's 47th edition of the festival.
   Meanwhile, some critics at the festival have blasted ``Henry and
June,'' a controversial American movie about Henry Miller that has
earned an ``X'' rating for its erotic scenes.
   But many critics at the festival, which ends today, also have
signed a petition urging the repeal of the ``X'' rating on grounds
that it limits artistic freedom.
   Set in the literary scene in Paris in the 1930s, the film is
based on sections of the diaries of Anais Nin and the
autobiographical novels of Miller, an American expatriate. Both
Miller and Nin were entranced with the young June Smith.
   ``It was just a bad film,'' commented Irene Bignardi, critic of
Rome's La Repubblica, after the world premiere Friday. ``But even
Americans who are rather infantile would not be shocked by it.''
   ``It's enough to put you off sex,'' quipped The Guardian's
critic, Derek Malcolm.
   The film stars Swedish-American Uma Thurman, whose first break
came as a seduced adolescent in Stephen Frears' ``Dangerous
Liaisons.'' It was directed by Philip Kaufman, whose other movies
include ``The Unbearable Lightness of Being'' and ``The Right
Stuff.''
   Produced by Universal Pictures, the film was rated ``X'' last
month by the U.S. Motion Picture Association's rating board,
meaning no one under 17 can be admitted for viewing.
   Universal has vowed to appeal the rating in an attempt to
challenge the 22-year-old rating system.
</TEXT>
